[## LECTURE 7.1 — GITHUB BRANCH PROTECTION: NO DIRECT PUSHES TO MAIN]

1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:30,000
You have the most secure, available, perfectly logged system in the world.
But what happens when a developer pushes directly to main?
Or merges a PR without review?

2
00:00:30,000 --> 00:01:00,000
One bad merge and your compliance is gone.
Change management, CC8.1, requires that all changes follow a controlled process.
No exceptions. Not for emergencies. Not for small fixes.

3
00:01:00,000 --> 00:01:30,000
Hi there, and welcome to Phase 7 of our SOC 2 journey.
In this phase, we are building a complete change management system
that auditors love.

4
00:01:30,000 --> 00:02:00,000
GitHub branch protection, PR requirements, pre-merge validation,
ArgoCD GitOps, rollback procedures, database migrations,
canary deployments, and complete change audit trails.

5
00:02:00,000 --> 00:02:30,000
By the end of these two hours, every change to your system
will be reviewed, tested, approved, and traceable.
From commit to production.

6
00:02:30,000 --> 00:03:00,000
Let me start with the foundation. Branch protection.

7
00:03:00,000 --> 00:03:30,000
Apply branch protection via the GitHub CLI.
Required status checks must be strict.
The branch must be up to date with main before merging.

8
00:03:30,000 --> 00:04:00,000
The required status checks include secret scan, Trivy filesystem scan,
dependency scan, Ruff, MyPy, unit tests, and Conftest validation.
All must pass before a PR can merge.

9
00:04:00,000 --> 00:04:30,000
Required pull request reviews. Set required approving review count to two.
Two people must approve. One can miss something. Two is harder.

10
00:04:30,000 --> 00:05:00,000
Dismiss stale reviews. If you push new code after approval,
approvals are dismissed. No sneaking in changes.

11
00:05:00,000 --> 00:05:30,000
Require code owner reviews. If you change security code,
the security team must approve.
Require last push approval. The reviewer who approved
must have approved the most recent commit.

12
00:05:30,000 --> 00:06:00,000
Enforce admins. Even administrators cannot bypass branch protection.
Require linear history. No merge commits. Only rebase or squash.
Clean audit trail.

13
00:06:00,000 --> 00:06:30,000
Allow force pushes false. Force pushing overwrites history.
That is not allowed.
Allow deletions false. Branches cannot be deleted through the API.

14
00:06:30,000 --> 00:07:00,000
Now verify the protection.
gh api to get the branch protection settings.
Extract required reviews count, dismiss stale, code owners required,
force push allowed, and admin enforced.

15
00:07:00,000 --> 00:07:30,000
Save the branch protection configuration as evidence.
Save it to soc2-evidence under today's date in CC8.1.
Call it branch-protection dot json.

16
00:07:30,000 --> 00:08:00,000
Test that protection works.
Attempt a direct push to main. It should fail.
The error says protected branch update failed.
At least two approving reviews are required.

17
00:08:00,000 --> 00:08:30,000
Attempt a force push to main. It should also fail.
The error says cannot force push to a protected branch.

18
00:08:30,000 --> 00:09:00,000
Your lab exercise is to configure branch protection on your main branch.
Verify you cannot push directly.
Create a PR and verify it requires approval.
Test that force pushes are blocked.

19
00:09:00,000 --> 00:09:30,000
In the next lecture, we will configure CODEOWNERS.
To automatically request review from the right teams.


