[## LECTURE 7.6 — DATABASE MIGRATIONS: REVERSIBLE ALEMBIC WITH DOWNGRADE TESTING]

78
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:30,000
Application rollbacks are easy.
Database migrations are hard.
If you add a column and then roll back,
you cannot just undo the application. The column still exists.

79
00:00:30,000 --> 00:01:00,000
You need migrations that are reversible.
Alembic supports downgrade migrations.
Every upgrade must have a corresponding downgrade.

80
00:01:00,000 --> 00:01:30,000
Here is a reversible migration.
Add a column called query_classification to analysis_history.

81
00:01:30,000 --> 00:02:00,000
In the upgrade, first add the column as nullable.
Add an index on the new column.
Then backfill existing rows. Set query_classification to general for all nulls.

82
00:02:00,000 --> 00:02:30,000
After backfill, alter the column to be not nullable.
This avoids locking the table for a long time.

83
00:02:30,000 --> 00:03:00,000
In the downgrade, reverse the order.
First, alter the column to be nullable again.
Then drop the index. Then drop the column.

84
00:03:00,000 --> 00:03:30,000
Now test the migration locally.
alembic upgrade head. Upgrade succeeds.
alembic downgrade minus one. Downgrade succeeds.
alembic upgrade head again. Re-upgrade succeeds.

85
00:03:30,000 --> 00:04:00,000
Verify the column exists after upgrade.
psql backslash d analysis_history. Look for query_classification.
Verify it is gone after downgrade.

86
00:04:00,000 --> 00:04:30,000
The CI migration test runs on every PR that touches migrations.
It starts a PostgreSQL test container.
It applies all migrations. It tests downgrade. It tests upgrade again.

87
00:04:30,000 --> 00:05:00,000
This ensures every migration is reversible.
If a migration breaks the downgrade path, the PR is blocked.
Your lab exercise is to create a reversible migration.

88
00:05:00,000 --> 00:05:30,000
Test upgrade and downgrade locally.
Push to PR and verify CI passes.

89
00:05:30,000 --> 00:06:00,000
In the next lecture, we will generate a monthly change audit report.
Complete traceability from commit to production.


